William Rowe (browe@netcom.com) wrote:

: You will not want to use a CRC. These are relatively easy to fool. What you
: probably need is SHA, MD-5 or MD-4. Source code for any of these can be 
: obtained from a variety of ftp sites.
: -- 
: _______________________________________________________________________________
: William Rowe                                                   browe@netcom.com
: MD5OfPublicKey: F29A99C805B41838D9240AEE28EBF383

	Just out of curiosity, how many possible CRC values are there for 
a given number of bytes in a plaintext.  Suppose you used a CRC 32 
function as a one-way hash for a key phrase, then used that 32 bit value 
as a seed for a multiplicative congruential (or other) random number 
generator to generate a key as long as the plaintext.  Any estimate on 
the number of possible keys?  Relatively speaking, how secure would such 
an algorithm be?


